Some of the problems in Poland are that productivity has fallen sharply both in factories and on the farms, and the people feel they don't get enough meat and other basic goods. Today the Polish economy is running 7 billion dollars short, and they need to borrow this money from outside the country. Let me ask you whether you favor or oppose each of these courses of action that might be taken by the U.S. in the case of Poland. Item: The U.S. could lend the 7 billion dollars to Poland, but would insist that the Russians give the Polish people much more freedom of speech and human rights and much less economic dictation from government than they now have

As it works now, Social Security payments, payments to the handicapped and to those on government pensions, and other federal benefits are indexed to rises in the cost of living. As the Consumer Price Index goes up, the amount of benefits goes up by the same percentage. Those who favor this system feel those who get the benefits should not suffer from increases in cost of living. Others feel that by increasing the amount of benefits as prices go up, government spending goes up and that makes inflation still worse. All in all, do you favor or oppose indexing these benefits to the cost of living?

Some Democrats in Congress are working on a tax bill as a substitute for the Kemp-Roth tax proposal which calls for a reduction of the federal personal income tax rate 10% each year for the next three years, which many congressmen think is too inflationary. Item: Increasing the amount an eligible individual can set aside for retirement in an IRA plan as a deduction against taxes from $1,500 to $10,000

Another proposed way of keeping government benefits in line with the cost of living would be to index the benefits to changes in wages. In other words, benefits would increase according to the annual average rise in wages. If, over the past few years, the benefits had been geared to wage increases rather than price rises, the government would have saved 6.5 billion dollars a year. Would you favor or oppose a new system, under which both price and wage increases would be looked at and the benefits would go up by whichever index went up least?

At the same time, many people believe that more federal money is needed to properly finance Social Security and to build up our military defenses to keep ahead of the Russians. On each purchase you made, you would pay a 10 cent additional sales tax for every dollar you spent. Supporters say this legislation (that would require health insurers to offer coverage to people who lose or change jobs, without regard to pre-existing medical conditions, as long as they pay their insurance premiums) would help protect some people who change or lose their jobs from being denied the opportunity to continue their coverage and would make insurance available to more Americans. I'm going to give you some information about how Medical Savings Accounts would work, and then ask your opinion of them. Medical Savings Accounts would allow employers to purchase plans with lower premiums that would only provide coverage after the employee pays about...$ 2,000 a year in medical bills. Any savings the employer gets by offering this less expensive plan could be put into the employee's tax-free medical savings account, which could be used to help pay the first...$ 2,000...in medical bills or any additional medical expenses. If it is not spent, it could be withdrawn as additional taxable income or saved to spend on next year's medical bills. Supporters of Medical Savings Accounts say this will lower individuals' health care costs because it would give individuals the incentive to spend their own money more carefully. They also say this would reduce hassle for people to go to a doctor of their own choice without getting the approval of the insurance company. Opponents say that because people would have to pay the first...$ 2,000...for doctor and hospital visits at the time they receive care, Medical Savings Accounts would discourage people from getting needed services and preventive care. They also say that because healthier people are more likely to sign up for Medical Savings Accounts, this would leave sicker people paying higher premiums. After hearing these arguments, do you favor or oppose this proposed legislation to create Medical Savings Accounts, or don't you know enough about these issues to have an opinion?
